ple blink function in Arduino:\n                <pre><code>\n                void blink2() {\n                        // Function name: blink2\n                        // Return type: void (does not return any value)\n                        // Function body: Contains the code to be executed when the function is called\n\n                        digitalWrite(2, HIGH); // Turn the LED on\n                        delay(1000);           // Wait for 1 second\n                        digitalWrite(2, LOW);  // Turn the LED off\n                        delay(1000);           // Wait for 1 second\n                }\n                </code>\n                </pre>\n        </div>\n  </details>\n\n  <details>\n        <summary>NEW: Calling a Function</summary>\n        <div class=\"description\">\n                To use the function, you simply call it by its name followed by parentheses:\n                <pre><code>\n                void setup() {\n                        pinMode(2, OUTPUT); // Set pin 2 as an output\n                }\n\n                void loop() {\n                        blink2(); // Call the blink2 function to blink the LED\n                }\n                </code>\n                </pre>\n                In this example, the <code>blink2</code> function is defined once and can be called multiple times within the <code>loop</code> function. This helps to keep the code clean and avoids repetition.\n        </div>\n  </details>\n\n  <h2>Hints</h2>\n  <ol class=\"hints\">\n    <li>Start by implementing the function body of blink2</li>\n    <li>Once you can turn on LED 2, see if you can blink it multiple times using a for loop</li>\n  </ol>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n\n"}